HEALTH OF A NODE
.break 
.skip 3
.left margin 10
I.   PURPOSE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
This procedure outlines methods of obtaining information relative to a
node's general health without interrupting users of that node.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  REQUIREMENTS
.SKIP 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1. XRAY access to the target node.
.left margin 22
.indent -4
2. Access to an unused slot within ISIS nodes.
.left margin 22
.indent -4
3. Access to LOADII or ELF IF the target node is an ISIS machine.
.left margin 22
.indent -4
4. Access to the file: SLCRSH.NIB if the target is an ISIS node.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III. PROCEDURES
.skip 1
.left margin 14
I.  To determine fundamental condition of the node:
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1.  Log into XRAY in the target node.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
2.  In response to the XRAY prompt type: ND
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
3.  Observe the XRAY output and note the following:
.skip 1
.left margin 22
a.  Elapsed time since "NODE FIRST CAME UP"
.SKIP 1
.LEFT MARGIN 23
.indent -1
(This is time since node was last loaded with code.)
.skip 1
.left margin 22
b.  Elapsed time since "NODE LAST CAME UP"
.skip 1
.left margin 23
.indent -1
(This is time since node last recovered from a crash.)
.skip 1
.left margin 22
c.  The crash COUNT, TYPE and ADDRESS.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
d.  The STATUS of the lines.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
e.  The ERRATE of the lines.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
f.  The TIILNK NEIGHBORS DOWN list.  These are neighbors which were
specified for this node in its TYM file but which have not communicated
with the target node since it was last loaded with code.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
4.  At the XRAY prompt type: CL xx .
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
a.  THE QUALITY XX WILL BE THE NUMBER OF THE MOST RECENT CRYPTO LOGGER
messages you wish to view.  (XRAY expects xx to be entered in HEX.
A maximum of 256 (DECIMAL), ie. FF (HEX), messages can be displayed.)
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
b.  Observe the XRAY crypto logger output for indications of kernel
overloads, line anomalies, slot reports, etc.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
5.  Again at the XRAY prompt type: NS
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
a.  Observe the EXCT (Executive Loop Count) value.  It should be greater
than 40 on a properly loaded node.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
b.  Observe the EXLW value.  (This is lowest Executive Loop Count which
the node has experienced since the values were last reset.)
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
c.  Observe the EXWH value.  (This is the greatest Executive Loop Count
which the machine has experienced since the values were last reset.)
.skip 1
.left margin 33
.indent -7
NOTE:  The EXCT, EXLW and EXWH counts can be reset by typing: NS Z IN 
       response to the XRAY prompt.  This will allow the user to observe
       Executive Loop Count behavior during specific time frames
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
d.  Observe the TOTAL value for CODE DELAY and H-WARE DELAY.  The value
should be less than 50.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
6.  At the XRAY prompt type: KS xxxx (where xxxx = the node number of a 
neighbor).
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
a.  Observe the PACKET OVERHEAD values but remember that overhead is 
inversely proportional to data traffic.  The overhead remains roughly
fixed and if there is little data on the line, the percentage of 
overhead will be driven up.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
b.  Observe the BANDWIDTH utilization.  It should be less than 60% and
not greater than 70%.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
c.  Observe the TOTAL for LINK DELAY.  It should be less than 50 ms.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
d.  Observe the OVERLOAD COUNT.  This is the number of times the RMAKE
routine could not service all channels with data within 500 ms.  A
threshold of 10/min exists for this measurement.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
e.  Observe the SATURATION COUNT.  This indicated the number of times the 
link was never idle for a 1/2 second period.  A threshold of 30/min exists
for this measurement.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
f.  Observe the BACKLOG COUNT.  This is the number of times the RMAKE 
routine could not make a packet due to a closed window.
.skip 1
.left margin 33
.indent -7
.nofill
.nojustify
NOTE:  The KS command should be exercised on every active neighbor.
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
II.  To obtain CRASH TABLE information from a running ISIS node:
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1.  Using LOADII or ELF load SLCRSH.NIB into an unused slot in the target
node.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
2.  Log into DDT in the target node.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
3.  Enter the slot just loaded with SLCRSH.NIB.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
4.  Run SLCRSH by typing ?STAT at the DDT prompt.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
5.  SLCRSH will return information relative to the node, the node type,
version of code, crash count and the time the node was last taken over by
the supervisor.  It will also display the SUMMARY CRASH TABLE, the DETAIL
CRASH TABLES, REGISTER SET 0 and F contents, MAC Status and Segmentation
Register contents.
.SKIP 2
.left margin 15
COMMENTS:
.skip 1
.left margin 18
With reasonable care being used while working in DDT, the procedures 
outlined above will not be disruptive to users of the node.
