REMOVING USERS FROM ISIS SLOTS
.break
.skip 3
.left margin 10
I.   PURPOSE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
This procedure allows a user to clear another user from a specified slot.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  REQUIREMENTS
.skip 1
.left margin 18
1.  License to access slot
.skip 1
.left margin 28
.indent -4
A.  L.SOA - License to log into slot 0
.left margin 28
.indent -4
B.  L.SYA - License to log into slot 0FF (The ISIS System)
.left margin 28
.indent -4
C.  L.E.  - Normal Execution Access (Permits the starting and halting of a
slot)                                                        
.skip 1
.left margin 18
2.  DDT access to node
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III. PROCEDURE    
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
1.  Log into DDT in the target node.                               
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
2.  Type in a slot number other than the number of the slot to be cleared.
When the "*" prompt appears, the user is connected to the slot.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
3.  Type "?WHO".  DDT outputs a table showing the current status of each
slot.  The * to the right of the slot _# shows that you are the active user in
that slot.  The @ to the right of the slot _# shows the active         
users in the other slots.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
4.  Type in "?PORT".  Lists the users and the kernel port numbers assigned
to them.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
5.  Type in "?HANG XX".  With "XX" being the port number of the user removed.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
6.  Type "?WHO".  To verify slot is now cleared of the "@" indicator.  The username
will remain.  Now slot is clear and can be accessed.
