ISIS: MEMORY ALLOCATIONS
.break 
.skip 3
.left margin 10
I.   PURPOSE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
This procedure describes the process for determining the memory allocations
made to the various slots in an ISIS node.  This procedure is applicable to 
those instances where dumps of the code from lowest memory through the 
entirety of some specific slot is  required.  For instance, dumps are often 
required starting with low memory and including the entirety of SLOT 0.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  REQUIREMENTS
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
1.  Access to the BND file for the node on which the memory allocations are
to be determined.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
2.  Access to the utility program MERLIN.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III. PROCEDURE   
.SKIP 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
1.  Log into a system where MERLIN and the node's BND file are accessible
or can be made accessible.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
2.  At the executive prompt, type: R MERLIN
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
3.  At MERLIN's prompt, type: RUN
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
4.  In response to  MERLIN's "ENTER KERNEL FILE NAME" prompt, type the file
name for the BND file.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
5.  In response to MERLIN's "SLOT x PRESENT OPTION:" or the "SLOT xx NOT
PRESENT OPTION" prompts, type: /N
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
6.  Repeat STEP 5 until the prompts cease and the SLOT MAP is printed. 
The SLOT MAP will have the form:
.skip 1
.left margin 10
.right margin 75
.center 84
SLOT MAP
.break 
.skip 1
.LEFT MARGIN 18
.nofill
.nojustify
SLOT BEGINS ENDS
 0   15400  62C00  <----As an example, to dump the entire
 1   66100  714FF       node from Loc 0 through all of        
 2   71500  794FF       Slot O, addresses through                       
 3   79500  860FF       62C00 would have to be dumped.                 
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
7.  MERLIN will then return to the system's executive prompt.
.skip 2
.left margin 15
COMMENT:
.skip 1
.left margin 18
This process is useful for determining if memory errors at some specific
locations fall within a slot that is experiencing distress.
