.center 84
NETWORK OPERATIONS PROCEDURES
.break
.skip 2
.center 84
ISIS SLOT FAILURE AND RECOVERY
.BREAK
.skip 3
.left margin 10
I.   PURPOSE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
This procedure describes the techniques for trouble-shooting a failure of
an ISIS slot and the means by which the slot may be restored to service.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  REQUIREMENTS
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.nofill 
.nojustify
1. Knowledge of TYM files.
2. Ability to use DDT.
3. Access to loading facility, LOADII or ELF.
4. Access to the SLOT CODE for the slot that is down.
.fill
.justify
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III. PROCEDURE
.SKIP 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
1.  Make a determination of the slot(s) associated with the problem reported
or detected.  
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
2.  Log into DDT in the node(s) containing the slot(s) which are considered
suspect.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
3.  At the "slot_#" prompt, type in the number to the slot that is to be
checked.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
4.  When the "*" prompt appears, the user is connected to the slot.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
5.  Look for any greeting message to the slot that might indicate trouble,
ie. "HALTED" or "STOPPED", etc.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
6.  ALWAYS type ?HOST in the slot.  If "Dispatcher indicates slot is down"
shows, this is a definite response that the slot is down.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
7.  Should the slot be running a constant "RESTART", also referred to as
"crashing continuously", the "H" command should be issued.  This will halt
the slot.  (L.H. license is required for this command.)
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
8.  Type ?HIST for a history of any slot halts.  Look for the slot that is
being checked to see when it stopped running.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
9.  Exit from DDT by typing 2 "Z"'s.  
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -5
10. Run the CRASH program.  This may give some valuable information as to the
crash count of the slot as well as the crash id.  Manual examination of the
slot crash table can be done while in the slot using ISISII manual for cross
reference of crash table definitions.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -5
11.  Make certain the slot is halted and then dump the slot, using the "U" command in LOADII.  This will allow the
software support to analyze the software in the condition it was in when
the slot stopped operating.  (The kernel host of the target node and the target slot
number will be necessary for this step.)
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -5
12. Reload the slot using the "S" command in LOADII.  Load the production
code for the slot.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -5
13. Log back into the node containing the slot.  Repeat STEPs 3 through 6.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -5
14. If the slot is back up, there will be a report as to the condition of
the host when the ?HOST is issued.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -5
15. Should the slot still be down, the support agency should be notified
as soon as possible.  All information gathered in STEPs 9 and 10 (name of
the dump) should be passed onto them.                                                     
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -5
16. Exit the slot using the double "Z" command.
