.subtitle XRAY LINK PERFORMANCE
.index XRAY LINK
.SPACING 1
.upper case
.left margin 10
.right margin 75
.fill
.justify
.figure 5
.center 84
NETWORK OPERATIONS PROCEDURES
.BREAK
.skip 2
.center 84
XRAY: LINK/LINE PERFORMANCE
.break 
.skip 3
.left margin 10
I.   PURPOSE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
The purpose of this procedure is to define the methods by which information
relative to a link/line's performance can be obtained with the utility XRAY.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  REQUIREMENTS
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.nofill
.nojustify
1. Access to XRAY in the target node
2. Access to XRAY documentation
.fill
.justify
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III. PROCEDURE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
A.  To obtain the following parameters:
.skip 1
.left margin 24
.nofill
.nojustify
1. LINK STATUS
2. WINDOW SIZE
3. NUMBER of CIRCUITS
4. LINK and LINE TYPES
5. SPEED
6. TIME LINK ATTACHED/DETACHED
.FILL
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1.  Log into XRAY in one of the nodes into which the target LINK/LINE
terminates.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
2.  In response to the XRAY prompt, type: ND
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
3.  The above information will be printed out in response to the "ND"
command.
.skip 1
.left margin 28
.indent -6
NOTE: The ERRATE is an indication of the error rate which exists on the line.
      The best line condition is represented by no entry under ERRATE for that
      line.  The worst error rate is represented by ****.  A single "star" (*)
      would indicate a line is degrading, a double ** would indicate a poor
      line, a triple *** would indicate a bad line, and four **** would
      indicate a very bad line.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
B.  To obtain the following:
.skip 1
.left margin 14
.right margin 80
.nofill
.nojustify
1.  TP        TYPE of Link
2.  BO        BORI
3.  NL        Number of up lines attached to a LINK
4.  WS        WINDOW SIZE
5.  SP        Link SPEED Index
6.  NM        Link NUMBER
7.  NCHN      NUMBER of CHANNELS currently on the link
8.  ISEC      Pointer to INITIAL INPUT SECTOR DESCRIPTOR
9.  NRTR      Pointer to RECORD DESCRIPTOR of next rec for RTEAR
10. OSEC      Pointer to INITIAL OUTPUT SECTOR DESCRIPTOR
11. NRMK      Pointer to RECORD DESCRIPTOR of next rec for RMAKE
12. NRXM      Pointer for the RECORD DESCRIPTOR to be transmitted
13. LRT       Record NUMBER of the last record torn down
14. LAS       Record NUMBER of the last packet the node
15. LRM       Record NUMBER of the last record made
16. LAR       Record NUMBER of the last packet the neighbor ACKed
17. NAS       Record NUMBER of next ACK to be sent
18. BNOD      NEIGHBOR numbers
19. CHND      Absolute CHANNEL NUMBER of relative channel 0
20. B.PT      OFFSET into NIOTAB for beginning of permuter table
21. E.PT      OFFSET into NIOTAB for end of permuter table
22. ACHN      Number of ACTIVE CHANNELS on the link
23. VERS      Octal VERSION number from the neighbor
24. LINES     NUMBERS of all the LINES attached to the link
25. CMDCKTS   NUMBER of COMMAND circuits carried by the link
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
.right margin 75
1.  Log into XRAY in a node into which the link terminates 
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
2.  At the XRAY prompt, type: KD xxxx (where xxxx = neighbor node number
for th link)
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
3.  Observe the output for the above parameters.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
C.  To obtain following:
.skip 1
.left margin 14
.nofill
.nojustify
1.  NUMBER of LOGICAL LINK (Data) CHARACTERS IN and OUT
2.  NUMBER of PHYSICAL LINK CHARACTERS IN and OUT
3.  PACKET OVERHEAD IN and OUT
4.  BANDWIDTH UTILIZATION IN and OUT
5.  CHARACTERS PER SECOND PER CIRCUIT IN and OUT
6.  PACKET/SEC
7.  RECORDS/PACKET
8.  AVERAGE SIZE
9.  IN QUEUE link delay
10. RTEAR Delay
11. BUFFER Delay
12. OUT QUEUE 
13. XMIT Delay
14. TOTAL Delay
.fill 
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1.  Log into XRAY in the node at end of the target link.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
2.  At the XRAY prompt, type: KS xxxx  (where xxxx = node number of the
neighbor at the other end of the link)
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
3.  Observe the terminal output for the above parameters.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
D.  To obtain an XRAY CRYPTO Log Output of Specific Link Messages
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1.  It is possible to retrieve specific link related CRYPTO LOG outputs
from the pool of the "last 256" CRYPTO LOG messages by:
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
a. Logging into XRAY in a node at one end of a link.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
b. Typing:  CM n1 n2 ---- n8  (where n1 n2 ---- n8 are CRYPTO LOG 
message numbers)
.skip 1
.left margin 30
EXAMPLE:  CM 1 2 4 
.SKIP 1
.left margin 30
The EXAMPLE CM command shown above will yield all Link Up, DOWN, and 
DETACHED Crypto Logger messages that are in the last 256 Crypto Logger
messages generated by the node.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
2.  Use the XRAY documentation for Message Number definitions.
.subtitle
.page
.subtitle
.page
.subtitle PROBE LINE PERFORMANCE
.index PROBE LINE PERFORMANCE
.spacing 1
.upper case
.left margin 10
.right margin 75
.fill
.justify
.figure 5
.center 84
NETWORK OPERATIONS PROCEDURES
.break
.skip 2
.CENTER 84
PERFORMANCE OF LINK/LINE
.break
.skip 3
.left margin 10
I.   PURPOSE
.SKIP 1
.left margin 18
The purpose of this procedure is to define the methods by which information
relative to a link/line's performance can be recovered with the utility
PROBE.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  REQUIREMENTS
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.nofill 
.nojustify
1. Access to PROBE in the Active Supervisor
2. Access to PROBE documentation for Reference
.fill
.justify
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III. PROCEDURE
.SKIP 1
.left margin 14
A.  Obtaining LINE SPEED and STATUS
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1.  Log into PROBE in the active supervisor for the network containing
THE LINES WHICH ARE TO BE CHECKED.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
2.  To determine the current LINE SPEED and STATUS (Shut, Out Frozen)
can be obtained by using PROBE's "NODE" command.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
The resulting PROBE output will contain the desired information under the
heading LINK STATUS.
.skip 1
.LEFT MARGIN 39
.indent -13
PLEASE NOTE: An OUT status indicates a link is in the process of being returned
             to service after outage.
.skip 1
.left margin 39
If a link is out of service and attempts are not being made to restore it to
service, there will be no indication of the link under LINK STATUS.
.skip 1
.left margin 39
SHUT indicates that a network operator has taken the link out of service.
.skip 1
.left margin 39
FROZEN indicates that the link has been detached but has not yet been
declared down.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
B.  Obtaining a LINK LOGGER REPORTS, both Historical and Realtime
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1.  A HISTORY  of link reports or the ability to MONITOR link reports in 
realtime can be obtained with the PROBE "RNODE" "LOG" commands.  The
resulting output will contain link reports for all links on the specified 
node.  It is not possible with PROBE to restrict link reports down to a 
single link.  If TMCS is available, it's ability to restrict to a specific
link would make it a more logical choice for obtaining this type of 
information.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
EXAMPLE OF PROBE COMMAND SEQUENCE:
.skip 1
.LEFT MARGIN 39
.indent -12
RNODE xxxx  (where xxxx = one of the two nodes attached to the target link)
.skip 1
.left margin 39
.indent -12
LOG zzzzESX (where zzzz = the number of minutes back from the current
             time that you wish to back up the logger (ie. LOG 34ESX)
             or the date (julian) and time (GMT) from which you would 
             like to begin receiving information (ie. 241:12:45))
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
C.  Obtaining STATUS on all the Links Assigned to a Node
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1.  In PROBE only the SYNPRT command displays the status of all of the LINKS
assigned to the node.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
2.  To obtain the SYNPRT command output respond to PROBE's prompt with the
following sequence:
.skip 1
.left margin 27
.nofill
.nojustify
RLOG 1D0
SYNPRT xxxx (where xxxx = target node number)
LOG 1C
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
3.  The command output will be displayed on the terminal.  Even 
information relative to assigned but UNUSED links will be displayed.
.subtitle
.page
.subtitle
.page
.subtitle LINE PERFORMANCE
.index LINE PERFORMANCE
.spacing 1
.upper case
.left margin 10
.right margin 75
.fill
.justify
.figure 5
.center 84
NETWORK OPERATIONS PROCEDURES
.BREAK
.skip 2
.center 84
TMCS: LINK/LINE PERFORMANCE
.BREAK
.skip 3
.left margin 10
I.   PURPOSE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
The purpose of this procedure is to define the methods by which information
relative to a link/line's performance can be obtained with the utility TMCS.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  REQUIREMENTS
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.nofill 
.nojustify
1. Access to TMCS.                      
2. Access to TMCS documentation.
.fill
.justify
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III. PROCEDURE
.skip 1
.left margin 14
A.  Obtaining LINE SPEED and STATUS
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1.  Log into TMCS
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
2.  At the prompt, type: LIS SEL
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
3.  Make certain that the desired LINK and LINE is included under the "LINKS"
and "LINES" parameters.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -1
(If the LINK or LINE is not included it can be included again with the
RESTORE command providing both neighbors on the line or link are included
in the NODES parameter recovered via STEP 2.  Example: RESTORE LINK 
2001:2055)
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
4.  At the TMCS prompt, type: PROBE
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
5.  You may now issue Probe's "NODE" command and LINE SPEED and STATUS will
be printed under the heading "LINK STATUS".
.skip 1
.LEFT MARGIN 29
.indent -7
NOTE:  The status OUT means a link has been out and is in
       process or returning to service.
.skip 1
.left margin 29
The SHUT status indicates a network operator has taken the link out of 
service.
.skip 1
.left margin 29
The FROZEN status indicates that the link has been detached but has not
yet been declared down.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
6.  To return to TMCS from PROBE simply type: EXI in response to the PROBE
prompt.
.skip 1
.left margin 14
B.  Obtaining LOGGER Reports for LINK/LINES
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1.  Both Historical and Realtime LINK and LINE Logger reports can be
collected through TMCS.  It is possible, in fact, to restrict the logger
report to just specific LINES and/or LINKS.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
2.  Log into TMCS
.skip 1
.left margin 18
3.  At the TMCS prompt, type: LIS SEL
.skip 1
.left margin 18
4.  At the TMCS prompt, type the following:
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.nofill
.nojustify
IGNORE LINKS
IGNORE LINES
IGNORE EVENTS
IGNORE ISIS
RESTORE EVENTS 18 19 26 27 28 33 36 43 47 48 
RESTORE LINKS xxxx:yyyy wwww:zzzz  (Note 1)
RESTORE LINES aaaa:cc              (Note 2)
LOG bbbbbbbb                       (Note 3)
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.indent -8
Note 1:  xxxx yyyy and wwww zzzz are the node numbers on which the LINK
terminates.  Skip the "RESTORE LINKS" command if LINK messages are not
required.
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.indent -8
Note 2:  aaaa is a neighbor number on a line and cc is a port number which
could be obtained through XRAY's "ND" command or through PROBE's "SYNPRT"
command.  If LINE messages are not required, skip the RESTORE LINES command.
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.indent -8
Note 3:  bbbbbbbb represents the number of minutes you wish to have the
logger backed up or it can represent the DATE and TIME (GMT) from which
you want the logger to start.
.skip 1
.left margin 39
.nofill 
.nojustify
EXAMPLE:  LOG 304
          LOG 07/22/85 12:15
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
5.  TMCS will now output link and line logger messages for those lines and
links specified in the "RESTORE LINKS" and "RESTORE LINES" commands indicated
in STEP B.4 above.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
6.  By changing the events used, it is possible to see very specific logger
messages.  Reference the TMCS documentation for identification of message
numbers.
.left margin 14
.skip 1
C.  Using the TMCS DISPLAY Mode
.skip 1
.left margin 18
1.  Log into TMCS 
.skip 1
.left margin 18
2.  At the TMCS prompt, type: LIS SEL
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
3.  Verify that LINES and LINKS of interest are selected.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -1
(Use the "RESTORE LINKS", "RESTORE LINES", "IGNORE LINKS" and "IGNORE
LINES" commands to adjust the SELECTIONS to the existing requirements.)
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
4.  At the TMCS prompt, type: LIS PRO
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
5.  In the first line of the response a terminal type will be identified
just to the right of the user name with which you logged into TMCS.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
6.  If your terminal is not comparable to the terminal type identified
in the LIS PRO output, use the TMCS "TER" command to set TMCS up for your
specific terminal.
.skip 1
.LEFT MARGIN 37
.indent -7
Type:  TER ? in response to the TMCS prompt to obtain a list of possible
       terminal types.
.skip 1
.left margin 37
.indent -7
Type:  TER xxxxxxx to set TMCS for your terminal.
       (where xxxxxxx = the terminal type)
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
7.  Now in response to the TMCS prompt, type: DISPLAY
.SKIP 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
8.  A display listing LINK/LINE condition will then be presented.  Node
and host conditions will also be displayed.
