.center 84
TROUBLE-SHOOTING A NON-HARDWIRED INTERNODAL LINE
.BREAK
.skip 3
.left margin 10
I.   PURPOSE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
This procedure outlines a method for trouble-shooting a non-hardwired 
internodal line.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  REQUIREMENTS
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.nofill
.nojustify
1. Access to the LINTST.REL test file.
2. Access to a code loading utility, LOADII or ELF.
3. Ability to loopback modems on the line.
4. Knowledge of which physical ports connect to the line.
5. Access to PROBE, XRAY and/or TMCS.
.FILL
.justify
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III. PROCEDURE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
(Diagram A will be referenced in the following steps)
.skip 1
.left margin 5  
.nofill
.nojustify
#..........     .........                    .........    ..........
#:        :     :       :                    :       :    :        :
#: NODE A :__________:MODEM A:________________________________________:MODEM B:________: NODE B :
#:        :     :.......:   _\____Telco Line### :.......:    :        :
#:........:                                               :........:
.skip 1
                _^      _^                    _^      _^  
                _|      _|                    _|      _|   
                _|      _|                    _|      _|  
                _|      _|                    _|      _|    
                _|      _|                    _|      _|   
         ____________________________  MODEM A   MODEM B   _____________________________
DATA IO--____________________________)<---in AL   in AL-->(____________________________--DATA IO
                _|      _|                    _|      _|    
        ________________________________________________________________________________________    MODEM B    
DATA IO--_______________________________________________________________________________________)<-- in DL            
                _|      _|                    _|      _|   
     MODEM A   __________________________________________________________________________________________    
      in DL-->(__________________________________________________________________________________________--DATA IO       
.fill
.justify 
.skip 1
.left margin 22
NOTE: The points at which to loopbacks occur are depicted above.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
1.  If the problem is link error-rates, Log into XRAY in each of the nodes
into which the link terminates.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
a.  Type: ND in XRAY in both nodes to obtain WINDOW SIZE
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
b.  Compare the WINDOW SIZE parameters for the link.  If they do not match,
the TYM file(s) should be corrected and the new code should be generated
and loaded into the machines.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
c.  The health of the line/link should then be monitored to determine if
the errors on the line have stopped.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
d.  If the problem has been cleared, you need proceed no further.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
2. Using PROBE place a SHUT in the line and when XRAY indicates the
number of users on the line is sufficiently low, proceed to STEP 2.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
3.  Run a self test on both modems.  If either modem fails, request 
service on the modem and then go to STEP 13.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
4.  Run an end-to-end test between the modems to verify the line condition.
If the test fails, service on the line and possibly one or more modems is
required.  After servicing, go to STEP 13.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
5.  Place MODEM A and MODEM B in AL loopback (LL if digital modems are
being used.)
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
6.  Using either LOADII or ELF start a load of the file LINTST.REL
from NODE A toward NODE B.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
7.  If the load utility shows that data is being "lost", you have an
indication that either NODE A is at fault or there is a cabling problem
between NODE A and MODEM A.  (A fault in MODEM A which was not detected
during self testing is also remotely possible.)  After corrective action has
been taken, go to STEP 13.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
8.  Terminate any loads in progress and using LOADII or ELF start a load
of the file LINTST.REL from NODE B toward NODE A.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
9.  If the load utility shows that data is being "lost", you have an
indication that either NODE B is at fault or that there is cabling
problem between NODE B and MODEM B.  (A fault in MODEM B which is not
detected during self-testing is also remotely possible.)  After
corrective action has been taken, go to STEP 13.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -5
10. If no faults have been discovered thus far, verify the modem 
end-to-end test by placing MODEM B in DL (RT) loopback.  MODEM A
should be out of loopback.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -5
11. Terminate any loads in progress and using LOADII or ELF, load 
LINTST.REL through NODE A toward NODE B.  Any "lost" data will indicate
a previously undetected line or modem problem.  After servicing is
completed, go to STEP 14.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -5
12. Take MODEM B out of loopback and place MODEM A in DL (LT)
loopback.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -5
13. Terminate any loads in progress and using LOADII or ELF, load
LINTST.REL through NODE B toward NODE A.  Any "lost" data will indicate
a previously undetected line or modem problem.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -5
14. After servicing to clear any faults, verify the effectiveness of the
servicing by rerunning those test which failed.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -5
15. Take all modems out of loopback and terminate any loads which may be in
progress.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -5
16. Observe the line with PROBE, XRAY and/or TMCS for any further 
indications of trouble.
