.subtitle CIRCUIT TRACING
.index CIRCUIT TRACING
.spacing 1
.left margin 10
.right margin 75
.fill
.justify
.figure 5
.center 84
NETWORK OPERATIONS PROCEDURES
.break
.skip 2
.center 84
CIRCUIT TRACING
.break
.skip 3
.left margin 10
I.   PURPOSE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
This procedure describes the process by which existing circuits may be
traced through a TYMNET-II network.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  REQUIREMENTS
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.nofill
.nojustify
1.  Access to XRAY and/or PROBE
2.  Access to DDT
.fill
.justify
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III. PROCEDURE
.skip 1
.left margin 14
I.  Tracing a Circuit from a Stand-Alone Tymsat
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1.  Determine the port number in the Stand-Alone Tymsat where the circuit
originates.
.skip 1
.left margin 29
.indent -6
NOTE: Three methods exist for determining the origination port number in a
Stand-Alone Tymsat.  Use any one of the following techniques:
.skip 1
.left margin 28
.indent -4
1.  Obtain the origination port number (in decimal form) from the login
string displayed on the terminal.
.skip 1
.left margin 40
.indent -12
Example:####Please type your terminal identifier
.left margin 40
-2300-263-
.left margin 40
please log in:
.skip 1
.left margin 28
The origination port number is 263 (Octal) which converts to 179 (Decimal).
.skip 1
.left margin 28
.indent -4
2.  Use the XRAY command, AS U, before the user logs in and again immediately
after he logs in to detect the port on which he has landed.  The port number
will be displayed in Octal in the PORT field of the XRAY output.  Convert
the Octal port number to its Decimal equivalent.
.skip 1
.left margin 28
Example:####Prior to login----
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.right margin 80
.nofill
.nojustify
0001 PORTS IN USE OUT OF 256 -------->
PORT RLA DTR DSR RTS CP DPLX -------->
0210 FF  FF  FF  00  FF 00   -------->
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 28
Example:####After Login----
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.right margin 80
.nofill
.nojustify
0002 PORTS IN USE OUT OF 256 -------->
PORT RLA DTR DSR RTS CP DPLX -------->
0210 FF  FF  FF  00  FF 00   -------->
0263 FF  FF  FF  00  FF 00   -------->
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.right margin 75
.left margin 30
XRAY indicates that port number 263 appeared after the login.  The Octal 
number 263 then is converted to its Decimal equivalent, 179.
.skip 1
.left margin 28
.indent -4
3.  Use the PROBE command PSTAT immediately before and immediately after the
login to display the origination port number.  (The PSTAT response will
display the port number in its Decimal form.)
.skip 1
.left margin 28
Example:####Prior to login----
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.right margin 80
.nofill
.nojustify
PSTAT 2300 H0 0                    <--Command
HOST 0 PORT ARRAY 0   5 6 18 23 55 <--Response
PSTAT 2300 H0 1                    <--Command
HOST 0 PORT ARRAY 1   173 181      <--Response
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 28
Example:####After login----
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.right margin 80
.nofill
.nojustify
PSTAT 2300 H0 0                    <--Command
HOST 0 PORT ARRAY 0   5 18 23 55   <--Response
PSTAT 2300 H0 1                    <--Command
HOST 0 PORT ARRAY 1   173 179 181  <--Response
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.right margin 75
Notice that after the login Port 6 dropped but that was not of consequence to
us.  But also notice that Port 179 appeared coincidentally with the login
so Port 179 is the origination port number.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
2.  Perform the circuit trace using Probe TRACE command.
.skip 1
.left margin 28
Example:
.skip 1
.left margin 28
.right margin 80
.nofill
.nojustify
TRACE 2300 H1706 179                  <--Command
HOST 1706 PORT 179 2300 2315 2034 HOST 1897 PORT 1
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 28
.right margin 75
The Probe response to the TRACE command will then display the circuit as it
exists from the origination port to the termination port.
.skip 1
.left margin 14
II. Tracing a Circuit from an ISIS Slot Port
.skip 1
.left margin 18
If a circuit originates in at a port assigned to an ISIS slot, the path from
the port to the network is:
.skip 1
.left margin 32
.indent -4
1.  From the user port to the slot's dispatcher port.
.left margin 32
.indent -4
2.  From the dispatcher port to Slot 0's port into the network.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
The internal ISIS circuit path is depicted below.  The diagram also shows
the port numbers which the DDT query ?CT will return when the query is made
in the interface slot, Slot X, and in the node slot, Slot 0.
.skip 1
.left margin 10
.right margin 80
.nofill
.nojustify
###########..............                    ..............
           :  Slot X    :    Dispatcher      :  Slot 0    :
           :            :                    :            :
USER<---->Px<------------------------------------------->Pz<--->NETWORK
           :............:                    :............:
.skip 1
           _^                                             _^
           _|                                             _|
           _|<--------------?CT from Slot X-------------->_|
           _|               yield Px and Pz               _| 
.fill
.justify
.left margin 22
.right margin 75
Where:####Px = User Port Number
.left margin 32
Pz = Network Port Number
.skip 1
.left margin 18
The tracing method recommended below is not the most efficient means of doing
a trace because it presumes that the USER's port number is not known or if the
port number is known, it is presumed that the port cannot be correlated with
the Dispatcher Port Number.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
1.  Determine the Dispatcher port number at the port of origination of the 
circuit.
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.indent -4
1.  Log into DDT in the slot from which the user circuit will be originating
and type ?CT before the user circuit is built.
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.indent -4
2.  After the user circuit is built, again enter the DDT query ?CT from the
origination slot.
.skip 1
.left margin 28
Example: Response to ?CT before login:
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.nofill
.nojustify
PORT  1---->s4:2E
PORT  2---->s0:10
PORT  F---->s4:1D
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 30
Example: Response to ?CT after login:
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.nofill
.nojustify
PORT  1---->s4:2E
PORT  2---->s0:10
PORT  5---->s0:0E
PORT  F---->s4:1D
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 30
Notice that Port 5 came active coincidentally with the login.
.skip 1
.left margin 34
In the Example then:
.skip 1
.left margin 36
The USER Port Number = 5 (Hex)
.skip 1
.left margin 36
The Dispatcher Port Number = 0E (Hex)
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.indent -4
3.  Convert the Hexidecimal Network Port Number to its decimal equivalent
and perform the network circuit trace using the Probe command TRACE.
.skip 1
.left margin 40
.indent -12
Example: It was determined that the Network Port Number is equal to 0E which
converts to a Decimal Network Port Number of 14.
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.right margin 80
.nofill
.nojustify
TRACE 2041 H56 14                  <--Command
HOST 56 PORT 14 2041 2020 2063 HOST 345 PORT 6
.FILL
.justify 
.skip 1
.left margin 37
.indent -6
Note: In the TRACE command the node number (2041) and the host number
associated with the circuit (56) was used along with the Decimal Network
Port Number (14).
.skip 1
.left margin 37
If no host number is associated with origination point in the circuit
being traced the host number 0 can be used.
.subtitle
.page
.subtitle
.page
.subtitle SECURITY BREACH
.index SECURITY BREACH
.spacing 1
