SECURITY BREACH
.BREAK
.skip 3
.left margin 10
I.   PURPOSE
.SKIP 1
.left margin 18
To determine what data is being sent to the supervisor on a command circuit
for a login that is being flagged as garbage or as a security violation.
.SKIP 2
.left margin 10
II.  SCOPE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
Many bad login attempts are caused by poor Async data.  This data is garbled
by the communication equipment on the engine.  This procedure helps 
determine which.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III. PROCEDURE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
1.  Log into XRAY on the effected node with a super privileged name.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
2.  Set license in XRAY.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
3.  Issue a "TD 20" command with a printer turned on.  ("20" represents
the sup command port.  It will always be 20
and 21.)
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
4.  Issue a "TA 20" command with the printer turned on.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
5.  Issue a second "TA 20" command.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
6.  Look at the data for login request and the username.  If the name is 
readable, someone or program may be trying to get in.
.skip 1
.LEFT MARGIN 18
Many times the data will be garbage.  The "TA" command displays ASCII 
characters for the bit patterns.  This data may cause your terminal to
do unpredictable things.
.skip 1
.left margin 25
.indent -7
NOTE:  The XRAY logic will not display passwords.  No one can get to them. 
This command does not pose a security problem.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
7.  If you see garbage, halt and restart the node or slot (whichever is
applicable).  When DTR is present on an Async terminal port during initialization, the port is
hung on startup.  If the garbage continues immediately after the start,
then Tymnet hardware should be suspected.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
8.  If the problem does not reappear, then terminal equipment is suspect.
