.center 84
MUX IN NETWORK OPERATIONS
.BREAK
.skip 3
.left margin 10
I.   PURPOSE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
The ability to have a single terminal logged into multiple hosts and
utilities is essential to a network operations group.  Another feature    
of the Tymnet MUX is its ability to be used as a realtime communications
device.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  REQUIREMENTS
.SKIP 1
.LEFT MARGIN 18
.NOFILL
.NOJUSTIFY      
1. MUX slot and access to the MUX.
2. MUX code of version 4.00 or later.
.fill
.justify
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III. GENERAL INFORMATION 
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
1.  When usernames are "genned" into the MUX slot code, both LABELING
and HEAR parameters should be specified.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
2.  A sufficient number of names should be "genned" into the MUX code and
validated on the network for the MUX host so that all network operators
have access to the MUX.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
3.  In the following procedures (ESC) represents the depression
of the ESCAPE key.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
IV.  PROCEDURE
.skip 1
.LEFT MARGIN 18
.INDENT -4
A.  Using the MUX for Multiple Host and/or Utility Logins:
.skip 1
.left margin 18
1.  Log into the MUX
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
2.  At the MUX prompt, type: M xxxxxxxx
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.indent -1
(where xxxxxxxx = a label you would like to assign to the port being
used for the circuit that is about to be built)
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
3.  At the "PLEASE LOG IN" prompt, you proceed with a normal login process
appropriate for the desired host or utility.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
4.  To return to the MUX command level, type: (ESC)Z
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
5.  If you wish to build another circuit, go to STEP 2 again.                
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
6.  To transfer from a terminal circuit and return to the MUX command
level, you simply type: (ESC)Z .
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
7.  To transfer from the MUX command level to an existing circuit,
simply type: S xxxxxxx  (xxxxxxx = circuit label, see STEP 2).
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
8.  To backpressure a circuit, you must have the terminal currently
connected to the circuit and there must be at least one other
circuit built.
.SKIP 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
a.  Then simply type (ESC)B and the circuit to which your terminal is 
connected will be backpressured and your terminal will transferred to the
next circuit.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
b.  To release backpressure, you need only transfer back into the 
backpressured port by either transferring to that port from the MUX 
command level or by transferring to it from another circuit by typing
(ESC)B or (ESC)G .
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
9.  If circuits are not backpressured, any output from those ports will
be labeled and displayed on the terminal.  It is possible to display the 
output of a running logger, for instance, while also displaying the output
of a code loading facility such as LOADII or ELF.  You can, therefore,
watch the load proceed, know when the load ends and observe the logger
indications of the node and/or slot's return to service.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
B.  Using the MUX for Direct Terminal to Terminal Communications
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1.  If a network is spread out around the world, communications costs 
related to network operations can be reduced by utilizing the 
MUX's TALK and HEAR capabilities.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
2.  If you have need to communicate with someone, type: WHO at the 
MUX's command level.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
3.  If the user with whom you desire to communicate is logged in proceed as
follows:
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
a.  At the MUX command level prompt, type: HEAR ON
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
b.  Again at the MUX command level prompt, type: TALK xxxxxxx
.skip 1
.left margin 30
.indent -1
(where xxxxxxx = user name with whom communications must be established)
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
c.  Everything you type will now be transferred to the desired user as soon
as you terminate your input with a carriage return.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
d.  As soon as the other user performs STEP B.3.a and STEP B.3.b, whatever he types will
be transferred to your terminal when he types a carriage return.  
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
e.  To terminate the session, (ESC)Z should be typed.                         
The output of your terminal will now be directed back to the command level
within the MUX and the other user will no longer receive your terminal
output.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
f.  The other user should perform STEP IV.8.e to terminate his session with
you.  You may type HEAR OFF if you wish to discontinue your receipt of his
message before he terminates the session.
